==Civilian experience==
The battle of the Atlantic also resulted in civilian deaths. Hundreds died at sea as they tried to escape the bombings and evacuate to safer countries such as Canada, Australia, South Africa, New Zealand and India.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/history/world-war-two/10454718/Records-of-WW2-civilian-war-dead-published-online.html |title=Records of WW2 civilian war dead published online |newspaper=Telegraph |accessdate=2018-12-11}}</ref> The first civilian casualty occurred on September 3, 1939, the first day of the war, when the Cunard passenger liner ''Athenia'' was hit by {{GS|U-30||2}}, which attacked in the mistaken belief she was an armed merchant cruiser. Of the 1103 passengers on board, 118 drowned. The day after, Hitler ordered that no more attacks were to be made on passenger ships. Despite this, many more ships were torpedoed by German U-boats over the war years, many killing civilians. One of the most famous tragedies was the sinking of [[SS City of Benares|SS ''City of Benares'']] on 17 September 1940, 600 miles off the coast of Ireland. It was carrying 406 passengers, 100 of whom were children evacuees,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blog.nationalarchives.gov.uk/blog/remembering-city-benares-tragedy/ |title=Remembering the City of Benares tragedy &#124; The National Archives blog |publisher=Blog.nationalarchives.gov.uk |date= |accessdate=2018-12-11}}</ref> of which 87 children and 175 adults drowned. Not all attacks were as deadly, such as the sinking of the ''City of Simla'', which sunk off the coast of Glasgow, resulting in three dead and 347 survivors.

